answers.text: associating an abstract character with a particular code point

qas.question: How are some abstract characters represented in Unicode?

answers.text: a sequence of two or more characters

qas.question: What is another name for an acute accent?

plausible_answers.text: an ogonek, a dot above, and an acute accent

qas.question: What are format characters associated with?
What do sets of graphic characters directly correspond to?
What are all encoded as singular unicode characters?

context: The set of graphic and format characters defined by Unicode does not correspond directly to <b6_0>the repertoire of abstract characters<b6_0/> that is representable under Unicode. Unicode encodes characters by <a1_0>associating an abstract character with <b5_0>a particular code point<b5_0/><a1_0/>. However, not all <b7_0>abstract characters<b7_0/> are encoded as a single Unicode character, and some abstract characters may be represented in Unicode by <a2_0>a sequence of two or more characters<a2_0/>. For example, a Latin small letter "i" with <b4_0>an <b3_0>ogonek<b3_0/>, <a0_0>a dot above<a0_0/>, and an acute accent<b4_0/>, which is required in Lithuanian, is represented by the character sequence U+012F, U+0307, U+0301. Unicode maintains a list of uniquely named character sequences for abstract characters that are not directly encoded in Unicode.
